1 Hiroshima Data

The numbers of deaths from leukemia and other cancers among survivors of the Hiroshima atom bomb are given in the dataset Hiroshima.csv, classified by radiation dose received. The variable ‘Rad’ is approximately the midpoint of the radiation dose interval. We are interested in the dose-response association between radiation dose (Rad) and the cancer mortality rates for leukemia.

#Empirical logit function to prevent errors
emplogit <- function(y, n){ log((y +.5)/(n - y + .5))}

#Load in data
Hiro.dat <- read.csv('~/Desktop/Hiroshima.csv')
Hiro.dat

2 Plots

Our first plot will plot our observed proportions of Leukemia deaths relative to total cancer deaths versus radiation dose. This plot will also include an approximate 95% confidence interval for each data point.

#Create Proportion Column
Hiro.dat$prop <- Hiro.dat$leukemia/Hiro.dat$totalcancers

#=Create Approximate Upper and Lower Bounds
#For 95% CI's
Hiro.dat <- within(Hiro.dat, {
upper <- prop + 1.96 * sqrt(prop*(1-prop)/totalcancers)
lower <- prop - 1.96 * sqrt(prop*(1-prop)/totalcancers)
}
)

##Plot data points with CI's
with(Hiro.dat, {
  plot(Rad, prop, ylim = c(0,0.5), ylab = "Observed Proportion", xlab = "Radiation Dose",
       main = "Observed Proportion of Leukemia Deaths")
  arrows(Rad[1:6], lower[1:6], Rad[1:6], upper[1:6],
  length=0.05, angle=90, code=3, col=2)
  
}
)



Our second plot will plot the logit of the observed proportion versus radiation dose.

with(Hiro.dat,
plot(Rad, emplogit(leukemia, othercancer), main='Observed Logit Proportion of Leukemia Deaths',
xlab='Radiation Dose', ylab='Logit Proportion')
)



From these plots, we observe that there appears to be some positive correlation between radiation dose and the proportion of leukemia deaths.

3 Fit the glm models

We’ll try a number of logistic-style models, including logit, probit, and complementary log-link models. These three models are denoted by, \[\text{logit}(\pi_{i}) = \text{log}(\frac{\pi_i}{1- \pi_i}) = \beta_{1} + \beta_{2} \cdot \text{Rad}\] \[\text{probit}(\pi_{i}) = \Phi^{-1}(\pi_{i}) = \beta_{1} + \beta_{2} \cdot \text{Rad}\] \[\text{cloglog}(\pi_{i}) = \text{log}[-\text{log}(1- \pi_{i})] = \beta_{1} + \beta_{2} \cdot \text{Rad}\] respectively, where \(\pi_{i}\) is the probability of a cancer death being caused by leukemia given radiation dose \(\text{Rad}_{i}\), and \(\Phi(z)\) is the standard normal cdf.

#Logit-link Function
Hiro.glm1 <- glm(cbind(leukemia, othercancer) ~ Rad, family=binomial(link="logit"),
data=Hiro.dat)
summary(Hiro.glm1)

From these models, we can choose the one which best minimizes Akaike’s Information Criterion (AIC), and overall residual deviance. In this case, the complementary log-link model minimizes both relative to the other two models, so we choose the model:
\[\text{cloglog}(\pi_{i}) = \text{log}[-\text{log}(1- \pi_{i})] = -3.618 + 0.013 \cdot \text{Rad}\]
When testing \(H_{0}: B_{i} = 0\) for \(i = 1,2\), versus alternative \(H_{1}: B_{i} \neq 0\), we obtain p-values which are both significantly less than \(\alpha = 0.001\) (as seen in the summary table above), so we can say with a high-degree of confidence that our regression coefficients are both nonzero. From this, we can deduce that there is some association between radiation dose and leukemia cancer mortality. It remains to check our model fit with goodness-of-fit statistics.

4 Plot the fitted model

We’ll show our chosen model as it compares to the other two.

with(Hiro.dat,
{
plot(Rad, prop, main='Cancer Mortality Rate for Leukemia',
xlab='Radiation Dose', ylab='Prop Died of Leukemia')
lines(Rad, fitted(Hiro.glm3), col=2, lty=1)
lines(Rad, fitted(Hiro.glm1), col=3, lty=2)
lines(Rad, fitted(Hiro.glm2), col=4, lty=3)
}
)

legend('bottomright', c("Cloglog","Logit","Probit"),
col=2:4, lty=1:3 ,bty="n")



We can see that the complementary log-link fits our data significantly better, however some of our data points appear far from the line. There are a number of factors which could have caused this. Rad is chosen to be the midpoint of the radiation dose interval, which might not be accurate to the true mean dosage for those sampled in that interval. Furthermore, small sample sizes for the larger radiation dose intervals may cause our collected data to be misleading. Overall however, our model seems to be a good fit.

Here, we perform the Pearson’s \(\chi^2\) test.

SIG <- qchisq(0.95,4)

X1 <- sum(residuals(Hiro.glm3, type='pearson')^2)
X1; paste('pvalue =', pchisq(X1, 4, lower.tail = FALSE))
## [1] 2.3789
## [1] "pvalue = 0.666443599786823"



We get a p-value of \(\approx 0.666\), so our model fit is adequate. Next, we check the pseudo-\(R^2\) value:

Hiro.glm0 <- glm(cbind(leukemia, othercancer) ~ 1, family=binomial(link="cloglog"),
data=Hiro.dat)
PseudoR <- (logLik(Hiro.glm0)-logLik(Hiro.glm3))/logLik(Hiro.glm0)
PseudoR
## 'log Lik.' 0.682668 (df=1)



This is a high pseudo-\(R^2\) value, so both of our goodness-of-fit tests show that our model fits the data well.

6 Residuals

with(Hiro.dat,
     plot(Rad, residuals(Hiro.glm1, "deviance"),
          xlab = "Radiation Dose",
          ylab = "Deviance Residual",
          main = "Deviance Residuals versus Radiation Dose")
)



From our plot, the median and mean deviance residual appears to be close to zero, so our model does not appear to be biased in either direction. Once again, this seems to support our model being a good fit.

7 Conclusion/Summary

Following the dropping of the atom bomb on Hiroshima, the numbers of deaths caused by leukemia and other cancers were noted for survivors. The goal of this research was to test for correlation between radiation dose and cancer mortality rates for leukemia based on these survivors (and develop a model for the phenomenon). After testing some models, we found that a complementary log log model was best fit for our data. This model suggests that with an increase in dosage of radiation comes an increase in relative cancer mortality rate for leukemia (See Cancer Mortality Rate for Leukemia graph above). The evidence seems to point towards leukemia occurring proportionally more under high dosages of radiation than other cancers.
